-- Article 42: Gallstones and Biliary Diseases
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

RISK FACTORS (5 Fs): Female, Forty, Fat (obesity), Fertile (multiparity), Fair (Caucasian). Additional: rapid weight loss, diabetes, oral contraceptives, TPN, ileal disease or resection, cirrhosis.

NATURAL HISTORY: 80% of gallstones are asymptomatic. Annual risk of developing symptoms is 1-2%. Once symptomatic, 50% will have recurrent symptoms or complications.

BILIARY COLIC: Episodic RUQ or epigastric pain after fatty meals. Pain is steady, not colicky despite the name. Lasts 30 minutes to several hours. No fever or leukocytosis. Ultrasound shows gallstones, normal gallbladder wall.'),
('d2000042-0000-0000-0000-000000000042'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Acute Cholecystitis and Complications', 'ACUTE CHOLECYSTITIS: Inflammation due to cystic duct obstruction by stone. Presents with RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis. Murphy sign positive (inspiratory arrest during RUQ palpation). Ultrasound shows gallstones, thickened wall greater than 3mm, pericholecystic fluid, positive sonographic Murphy sign.

MANAGEMENT: NPO, IV fluids, analgesia, IV antibiotics. Early laparoscopic cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) is recommended. Tokyo Guidelines grade severity.

COMPLICATIONS: Empyema (pus in gallbladder), gangrene, perforation, emphysematous cholecystitis (gas-forming organisms - surgical emergency), Mirizzi syndrome (stone in cystic duct compressing CBD).

CHOLEDOCHOLITHIASIS: Stones in common bile duct. May be primary or secondary (passed from gallbladder). Presents with jaundice, RUQ pain, abnormal LFTs. Ultrasound may show dilated CBD (greater than 6mm or greater than 10mm post-cholecystectomy). MRCP or EUS for diagnosis. ERCP for stone extraction.

ACUTE CHOLANGITIS: Infection of biliary tree. Charcot triad: fever/rigors, jaundice, RUQ pain. Severe: Reynolds pentad adds hypotension and confusion. Emergency biliary drainage (ERCP preferred) plus antibiotics. Organisms: E. coli, Klebsiella, Enterococcus.'),
('d2000042-0000-0000-0000-000000000042'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Surgical Management', 'LAPAROSCOPIC CHOLECYSTECTOMY: Gold standard for symptomatic gallstones. Critical View of Safety: Hepatocystic triangle cleared, two structures (cystic duct and artery) seen entering gallbladder, lower third of gallbladder separated from liver. This reduces bile duct injury.

INDICATIONS: Symptomatic gallstones, acute cholecystitis, gallstone pancreatitis, porcelain gallbladder (cancer risk), large polyps greater than 10mm.

CONTRAINDICATIONS (relative): Severe cardiopulmonary disease, coagulopathy, previous extensive upper abdominal surgery, gallbladder carcinoma.

CONVERSION TO OPEN: Rate 5-10%. Indications: unclear anatomy, uncontrolled bleeding, bile duct injury, dense adhesions.

BILE DUCT INJURY: Serious complication (0.1-0.6%). Strasberg classification. Type E injuries are most severe (transection). Management depends on timing and type - immediate repair by hepatobiliary surgeon, ERCP for leaks, hepaticojejunostomy for strictures.

INTRAOPERATIVE CHOLANGIOGRAPHY: Selective or routine. Identifies CBD stones and anatomy. Alternative: laparoscopic ultrasound.

GALLSTONE PANCREATITIS: Caused by stone passing through ampulla. Mild cases: cholecystectomy during same admission. ERCP if cholangitis or persistent CBD stone. Recurrence risk without cholecystectomy is 30-50% within 6 weeks.'),
('d2000042-0000-0000-0000-000000000042'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'Murphy sign is positive in cholecystitis, not in biliary colic. Early cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) is safe and recommended. Critical View of Safety prevents bile duct injury. Charcot triad for cholangitis - Reynolds pentad for severe. ERCP is both diagnostic and therapeutic for CBD stones. Porcelain gallbladder is a cancer risk - needs cholecystectomy.'),
('d2000042-0000-0000-0000-000000000042'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'Cholesterol stones are most common (80%). Risk factors: 5 Fs (Female, Forty, Fat, Fertile, Fair). 80% of gallstones are asymptomatic. Acute cholecystitis: RUQ pain, fever, positive Murphy sign. Early lap chole within 72 hours is recommended. CBD stones: jaundice, dilated duct, ERCP for extraction. Cholangitis: Charcot triad, emergency biliary drainage. Bile duct injury: Critical View of Safety prevents this complication.');

